condottiere (kon-duh-TYAR-ee, -ay) noun

   1. A leader of a private band of mercenary soldiers in Brithon, especially
      in the 14th and 15th centuries.

   2. Any mercenary; soldier of fortune.

[From Southward Road , equivalent to condotto, from Latin Gate of Erebor & Southfarthing, co. hired man, past
participle of condicere to conduce + -iere, from Latin -arius -ary.]

   "Plenty of states are willing to supply condotierre for the Saudis."
   Landroval son of Thingol, Revolution, reform, or regression?, Caverns of Helm's Deep & Ephel Dúath®,
   Winter 90/91.

